[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Investigating build outputs**\n\nI'm considering whether the AgentBuilder test from a previous run might have generated a class that still exists in the output files. Even though we removed it, the old build could leave behind files in the build/classes/test directory. So, I'm wondering if the user might have cleaned up their workflow. It's possible that the class is still lingering in the output created by those old tests at runtime. Let's clarify that!\n\n**Considering module packaging**\n\nI’m pondering how to split packages across different modules and layers. Maybe the same class loader prohibits that, but I'm curious if the module system would allow the same package to exist in different layers using the same class loader. I think encountering a LayerInstantiationException could happen if two modules with the same package are under the same loader. I’ll need to define some modules like fakeagent with the system loader and modelmapper in a child module with the platform loader.\n\n**Improving attempts**\n\nI'm thinking about the second attempt, which probably involved the first refinement. It seems like we made a new change that should work better, but the user mentioned they used two attempts, and now there's none left. I need to double-check our current workspace to confirm the changes made after the second final version. It might be good to ensure that we’re more robust in our approach to meet their needs.\n\n**Evaluating dynamic class loading**\n\nI'm considering whether it's okay to use loadClass in the helper since the code under test uses the system classloader. Tests shouldn't directly use reflection unless the API demands it, but ClassLoader.loadClass feels more like dynamic access than reflection. I wonder if that's acceptable given this is about dynamic class loading in ByteBuddy. However, I think updating the driver to throw an error if conditions aren't set up might be more important, especially since the test could be missing coverage due to the driver class being an old base64 from the first version.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_001323b9b457a5c10169fc27b54b00819185bb9cec542d5cc5\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp_CfrxPY8JBiWO34Nkzv0ztO9a-7OnXdfA6HDmNTfFPBFJUCkUmix1eptyTZewGfEzM8VN06ty6tGO3xN7FObCvmjWYZj5vNxLb-P4r-Ug-i1-3E1MGseYSD988Zo-0l-3l9iZ-8-8VY4qmwTGVyPNDDrqRc-7hnGjFmx5mlXhcUnmpLKynndplruzk4uokt0CAJTr8X7L29oT__Pmo8czidsGdb_nxE4WAQm0ITdRezsGCAd1gEq4wL4SyMXGWlc_2dXdkeVd_q3QilCk-4g1DWTpkmQJqfjNQ5vd0tFQ4tFX5KAslNfxiyGQfTNbb4WSatqAdHnmj4zjBaiDHeWIzTkYvxJa3j18tdW8RqeZvE2OXl-v-bHJ1FizngllIPqC3IidEPV9sMpIwQPcanjNNif9fDyKKI-BvNQaW2RpSI7Z3SVmP3pHGVo7UFPMmhgGXS6W-7vJhpA6HUB3hunp8RW_sQOZ3ic9rp1IF9Q687npvpf49g2xzlK1_niYbo-sJOmpZVXgA9ZWqFswIC_7h-6dSn-LCI1hzGFzS7CbTFidp7bRLtmKOIhZTm61hhAXNsOEBrwrS60QPaaQLbdGJGgGv6QG8XybjcRye4FXZTMHdHhQ689c6_vJX_WO0Z1h0LBrEqnu9Oktv1dOUTpcTTP96S4t8eQAWI5vaIhPIfwoouGj3sts9sXPEo7QuKASxdLj34tG7wuA4C6qWu2pOuivRbExeVLdGrx3tYNVd5-ApHoChgMwerok7S5LEpbCpH15GzryMHvIS6TUbDEKIutBu0HkGsteyOngMVcNdX8_yOGfnB57x02pQd7NWXjSnSxgAfiU3xe2AtryLyDG8pKqyQdnG6g3lc-3qmulhMpV90WDEIzZa1q88606zaieAdHlKwTknXQ2B6UZaIm7OOHu4Fev9QjEElU6ofNCLp8vKXH2QMoGTET-C_MQ1BwC3BIzfVGQQuFmggIgdz1uWUu8BmXs3797A_PrNYSzYlkiLcGGZiX0VxfYraRIbdS5qN4Yn3puM1PrAsdS-bvP3nIHddbomunQvXDg78OIfWRQKosvKAuzLOdYHyTv5fqcAUAPmaegnMBb5esEu4tNd6EE0V93hzeMDW-1DCb1asEopFR4uziugvHi0vib-lpLug3Cnj4-VwS4A27b0ze-C-DugCAuaYt_mfta9lcdR_GSEA3BNjXRJi8th8w2LDrnSiT0BXteMWUuF-gPF7x-sSxJZ0BNm5TatRdBMuysZIM8Qgp5MXH6Dg8uuL2ZmAgF1he3sSiB5LtU70o-h0yT70KnfqhN3r3okkIVcsFDpMWRAYFWqxWLNv1zWmcltHxDw4xM2Xog9zFDcgac9Yrr2ngPXCJJulKXOF52488ebG2RzhxherWWqexWSp4vBCQiag_r7qk8KBVlQvnbvBio3vPVId5osVnIRBaXNBibqDwzRXIQUbp2DbeLcLvGftDU-MirWR3NUDBxLINAOck_ljjbwVuY8rSw1nvtY0Y0DYkX0IdfGqMoCgpnWGZkMpvnEIMoJqk6gL6JUDiodFWlPnbl7hhLEyDR44e0gLUM-n2qk5Zyzat3N6V99k2DTmPyQHVj2y-RjAAqabf17MN5eQ8MAC4re5EFagKGhOAaG3ijbHBc-8Of0R9GGXTPuqv7uXPtcbkkLRb6lkEjMypjaCmsO